          <span class="uf-comment"># Strong content + genuine comparison tables</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 300k+ monthly organic visitors (Ahrefs estimate)</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Works because content quality matches domain promise</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. Local roofing — borderline EMD</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-old">Domain:</span> <span class="uf-new">denverroofingexperts.com</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Ranks for "Denver roofing" and variants</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Cannot expand to "roofing Colorado" naturally</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Brand building limited by over-specific name</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Generic product EMD — fails the trust test</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-old">Domain:</span> <span class="uf-new">buyipadcheap2024.com</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Year-appended = immediate trust red flag</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Low CTR due to spammy appearance</span><br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Penalized for thin affiliate content</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">EMD vs brand domain — which to choose</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use an EMD when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You're building a niche affiliate or comparison site</li>
              <li>The keyword maps to one clear, permanent service</li>
              <li>Local market recognition matters more than brand</li>
              <li>You have a content plan to support the domain promise</li>
              <li>The domain is readable and not spammy-looking</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a brand domain when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You plan to expand products or services</li>
              <li>Brand trust is a primary conversion driver</li>
              <li>You're building for the long term (5+ years)</li>
              <li>The keyword makes the domain look generic or untrustworthy</li>
              <li>You want social media handles to match easily</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for using EMDs in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Build genuine content depth first.</strong> The EMD is worthless without content that fully covers the topic. Plan at least 50 pages of quality content before committing to the domain.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid year-appended domains.</strong> <code>bestlaptops2024.com</code> becomes outdated instantly and signals low quality to users scanning SERPs.</li>
          <li><strong>Treat the domain like a brand.</strong> Design a real logo, write a real About page, publish an author bio, and build social profiles. Naked keyword domains with no brand signals get sandboxed.</li>
          <li><strong>Diversify anchor text in link building.</strong> EMDs attract over-optimized anchor text naturally, which is a link penalty trigger. Actively seek branded and generic anchors to balance the profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Use hyphens only if necessary.</strong> <code>best-plumber-austin.com</code> is harder to remember and looks worse than <code>bestplumberaustin.com</code>, but exact multi-word keywords sometimes require hyphens for readability.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor for thin-content flags in Search Console.</strong> If Google Search Console shows declining impressions after an algorithm update, add content depth immediately — the EMD signal amplifies quality problems.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — buying an aged EMD expecting instant rankings</div>
          <p>Aged EMD domains with backlink histories seem attractive but carry inherited penalty risks. Google disavow histories, past spam links, and PBN footprints follow the domain. Always audit an aged domain's link profile with Ahrefs or SEMrush before purchase. A clean new domain often outperforms a questionable aged EMD within 12 months.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common exact match domain mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Assuming the domain does the ranking work</strong> — content, links, and user signals still dominate over keyword domains.</li>
          <li><strong>Choosing an unreadable domain</strong> — <code>bestplumberaustintexas.com</code> is hard to say, spell, and remember.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring brand trust signals</strong> — no About page, no author, no social presence signals low credibility in Google's quality assessment.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-optimizing anchor text</strong> — when all external links use the exact keyword, it looks manipulative and triggers over-optimization penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting ultra-competitive head terms</strong> — EMDs cannot compete with established brand domains for terms like "car insurance" without massive authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Registering .net or .org EMDs</strong> — the weak ranking signal that EMDs carry applies primarily on .com; extensions matter far less.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
